			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> keynote:</span><br><i>Analysing Contributions</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/OegedeMoor.html">Oege de Moor</a></h2>
<ul><li>URL: <a href="https://www.sleconf.org/2012/Keynotes.html#invited-talk-jointly-with-gpce-by-prof-oege-de-moor-university-of-oxford">https://www.sleconf.org/2012/Keynotes.html#invited-talk-jointly-with-gpce-by-prof-oege-de-moor-university-of-oxford</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The talk is centered on a concrete tool/product (ODASA) that integrates analyses and dashboards to support engineering work.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> ODASA’s core value proposition is large-scale software analysis over code, histories, and tooling outputs to surface “objective facts.”
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The emphasis on directing maintenance/testing effort and tracking quality trends over time squarely targets maintenance and evolution concerns.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL">T6B: Industrial</span></a><ul><li> The framing is explicitly industrial (product by Semmle Ltd for large projects; later acquired by GitHub, but that’s beyond what you provided).
</li></ul></li></ul>
